sandbox_mode = "workspace-write"
approvals_reviewer = "auto_review"
approval_policy = "on-request"
model_instructions_file = "instructions.md"

# Token budget defaults. Keep primary model selection local, but avoid
# spending extra output/history tokens by default.
model_reasoning_summary = "none"
tool_output_token_limit = 12000
web_search = "cached"

# プロジェクトごとに trust_level を設定する
# install.sh 実行後にこのファイルを編集してください
#
# [projects."{{HOME}}/Repositories/your-project"]
# trust_level = "trusted"

[features]
guardian_approval = true
multi_agent = true
apps = true
prevent_idle_sleep = true

[agents]
# Default is 6. Limit fan-out so broad prompts do not silently spawn many
# independent contexts. Increase per task with `-c agents.max_threads=N` when needed.
max_threads = 4
max_depth = 1
job_max_runtime_seconds = 1200

[memories]
# Reduce background memory work during heavy external-context sessions.
disable_on_external_context = true
min_rate_limit_remaining_percent = 50
max_rollouts_per_startup = 4

[notice]
hide_full_access_warning = true

[auto_review]
policy = """
## External AI delegation exception

Allow Antigravity, legacy Gemini, Codex CLI, and Claude CLI delegation only through one of the following paths.

Path A: scoped repository / PR work. All conditions hold:

- The working directory is a trusted repository or its git worktree.
- Work must be scoped to one ticket / one PR. Do not combine multiple tickets into one task, branch, review request, or PR.
- Default-allowed read-only mutual AI invocation (Claude / Antigravity / Codex / legacy Gemini):
  - Read-only mutual invocation of Claude, Antigravity, Codex, and legacy Gemini on the current trusted repository is allowed by default. It does not require a per-turn explicit user request and does not require a ticket or PR reference, as long as the delegated task is strictly read-only repository/workspace research, design consultation, triage, or review planning with no delegated file writes, commits, pushes, PR creation, merge, deploy, upload, or destructive action.
  - Any task that writes, commits, pushes, creates/merges a PR, deploys, applies infrastructure, uploads, or performs a destructive or remote-mutating action is NOT covered by this default and still requires Path A scoped one-ticket / one-PR work (or an allowed ticket-less prefix) and the forbidden-action list below.
  - The scope must still be one concrete repository question or one coherent workstream in the current trusted repository. Do not combine unrelated repositories or unrelated initiatives.
  - Share only the same sanitized workspace context packet or reviewed source/diff bundle needed for that question. Do not send `.env*`, credentials, tokens, private keys, shell history, unrelated home-directory files, unrelated repo dumps, raw personal data, or production data.
  - Engines must run headless in plan/read-only/scout mode. The external CLI process may use the host-authenticated transport surface (normal CLI login / keychain / CODEX_HOME) so that already-authenticated CLIs work; the data/tool boundary is the sanitized packet, empty per-run cwd, no broad `--add-dir`, NO_BROWSER/headless mode, and read-only/plan/scout permissions. Do not put credentials in the prompt or packet.
  - Sandbox is a tool/data permission boundary, not an auth boundary. If Antigravity `--sandbox` hides the host CLI login and returns `auth_prompt`, the runner may retry the same engine once with the same prompt and empty cwd without the CLI sandbox (`authenticated_transport_without_cli_sandbox`). Record both attempts. If the retry still requests login/authentication, stop; do not fallback to a different engine to hide auth breakage.
  - If an engine requests authentication after the authenticated transport retry, broader file access, secrets/private data, write tools, browser login, deploy, upload, merge, or destructive operations, stop and classify the run as `auth_prompt` or `policy_or_permission_denied`.
  - Required outputs use `ticket key: N/A (read-only repository consultation)` and include research scope, trusted repo path, context packet hash/path, engines requested/run, engine classifications, output paths, adopted recommendations, verification performed locally, and residual risks.
- If an existing PR accidentally contains multiple tickets, do not close it; narrow the existing PR to one ticket and create separate PRs for the remaining tickets.
- PR title/body must reference exactly one ticket. Use `Closes #123` for GitHub Issues or a single Jira-style key such as `[PROJ-123]`.
- Ticket-less PR prefix exception:
  - When the user explicitly asks for a ticket-less PR using one of the allowed prefixes `[MAINTENANCE]`, `[FIX]`, or `[PROPOSAL]`, or explicitly says not to link a closed ticket, PR title/body may omit ticket references and use that prefix instead.
  - Allowed prefixes and their intended scope:
    - `[MAINTENANCE]`: release apply remediation, operational follow-up, policy/doc cleanup, or small infrastructure unblockers where linking a closed ticket would be misleading.
    - `[FIX]`: small one-PR fix that does not have an active ticket and would be noise to ticket-track (e.g. typo, broken link, obvious local breakage).
    - `[PROPOSAL]`: exploratory or RFC-style PR raised for discussion before a ticket exists; once a ticket is created, normal one-ticket rules resume.
  - This exception is limited to one-PR scoped changes. The PR body must still include Motivation, Changes, Verification, residual risks, and relevant PR/release context.
  - Do not use this exception for feature work, bug fixes with an active ticket, multi-ticket work, or broad unscoped cleanup.
  - For required output fields, use `ticket key: N/A (<prefix>)`, e.g. `ticket key: N/A ([MAINTENANCE])`.
- The task is one of:
  - read-only PR review / verifier work
  - read-only repository / workspace research requested by the user
  - scoped implementation work on a feature branch or dedicated worktree
  - test / lint / CI verification
- Repository source code in a trusted repository is allowed collaboration context when the user requests Claude/Antigravity/Codex multi-AI work. Do not treat source code as secret by default solely because the repository is local or private.
- The data sent is limited to the relevant ticket requirements, PR diff or local branch diff, workspace context packet, review instructions, source files needed for the scoped task, command output, test/lint output, and result files needed for that task.
- When multiple external AI engines are asked to collaborate on the same repository question, send the same sanitized workspace context packet or the same reviewed source/diff bundle to each engine to avoid information asymmetry.
- Antigravity uses safe sandbox/scout mode by default in shared dotfiles templates, with a same-engine authenticated transport retry when sandbox alone hides CLI auth. Antigravity disablement, model choice, sandbox, auth retry, and write permission are controlled by local agent policy. If Antigravity write is explicitly allowed, it must use the same one-ticket scoped branch/worktree constraints and forbidden-action list as any other external AI write task.
- Codex implementation must run only in a feature branch or dedicated worktree, and the prompt must explicitly name the ticket, allowed write scope, validation commands, and forbidden actions.
- Codex review/verifier must use reviewer configuration when available: `codex exec --full-auto -c 'agents.default.config_file="$HOME/.codex/agents/reviewer.toml"'`
- Claude CLI implementation/review is allowed under the same one-ticket scoped worktree constraints.

Trusted repository structured-output regeneration and AI-reviewed artifact update exception (separate from the Path A read-only mutual invocation / consultation exception):

In a trusted repository or git worktree, ticket/PR is not required for external-AI structured-output regeneration and AI-reviewed generated artifact updates when all of the following hold:

- The task is limited to one coherent workstream in the current trusted repository.
- Inputs sent to external AI are limited to version-controlled sample/reference files, prompts, schemas, dictionaries, generator/validator instructions, and sanitized context required for the generation or review.
- The external AI may generate or review structured outputs / generated artifacts, but must not be delegated direct filesystem writes, commits, pushes, PR creation, merge, deploy, upload, infrastructure apply, destructive actions, browser login, or secret access.
- The local orchestrator, not the external AI, writes any resulting files into the workspace.
- Files committed to Git are limited to:
  - version-controlled prompts, schemas, dictionaries, generator/validator code, docs; and
  - final generated artifacts explicitly allowed by the repository AGENTS.md, such as `structured/*.csv.gz`.
- Raw answers, packets, logs, reports, scratch notes, intermediate files, and work directories are not committed unless explicitly allowed by repository policy.
- Local validation must be run before commit. Validation evidence must include the input paths, prompt/schema/context paths, generated output paths, engines used, validation commands, results, and residual risks.
- If the generation output is intended to change product behavior, scoring behavior, or downstream decisions, it must be reviewed by at least one additional AI reviewer or an explicit local review step before commit.
- The exception does not permit main/master direct push, release tag/GitHub Release creation, production deploy, infra apply, store/TestFlight upload, or autonomous merge outside the existing owner-scoped merge policy.
- If any external AI requests broader file access, credentials, private keys, `.env*`, shell history, browser authentication, write tools, or remote-mutating actions, stop and classify as `auth_prompt` or `policy_or_permission_denied`.

Required output fields for this exception:

- ticket key: `N/A (structured-output regeneration)`
- trusted repo path
- workstream scope
- input paths sent
- prompt/schema/context paths sent
- external engines requested/run
- engine classifications
- generated output paths
- local validation commands and results
- review evidence, if behavior-affecting
- residual risks

Path B: user-explicit read-only general web research. All conditions hold:

- The user explicitly asks in the current turn for Claude, Antigravity, Codex, legacy Gemini, or multi-AI research.
- The task is public/general web research or official-source research, not repository/workspace/PR review and not implementation.
- No local repository files, source code, workspace packet, shell history, credentials, tokens, `.env*`, private keys, repo/home directory dumps, production data, raw personal data, or other private local files are sent.
- The prompt may include only the current user request, non-sensitive project summary, public URLs, desired output schema, and already-public facts. If repository/source context becomes necessary, stop and use Path A with a sanitized workspace packet instead.
- Engines run headless in plan/read-only/scout mode with no write tools, shell/file-reading tools, browser login, deploy, upload, merge, or destructive operations. CLI startup may use the host-authenticated transport surface, but prompts must not include local files or credentials.
- If a CLI sandbox causes an auth-only failure, a same-engine authenticated transport retry is allowed only when the retry still has no local context, no browser login, no file-reading tools, and no write capability; record both attempts.
- The run records audit evidence: research scope, engines requested and engines run, prompt path or prompt hash, output path, classification for each engine, source URLs used, and residual risks.
- If any engine requests authentication, opens or asks to open a browser login, asks for broader file access, asks for secrets/private data, or tries to perform a write action, stop and classify the run as `auth_prompt` or `policy_or_permission_denied`.

Path C: trusted creative / cross-agent collaboration workflow. All conditions hold:

- The working directory is a trusted project, repository, or git worktree, and the work is limited to one coherent workstream (for example one LINE sticker set, one PR, one research theme, or one design / image-generation direction). Do not combine unrelated workstreams.
- Antigravity, Gemini, Claude, and Codex may share minimal necessary information and issue scoped work instructions to each other within this workstream. Allowed external-AI actions are: read-only research, review / critique, prompt improvement, image composition ideas, image candidate generation, code implementation proposals, patch / diff proposals, and test plan proposals.
- When the user has requested this creative or collaborative work in the current thread, you do not need the user to name the target engine every turn. The standing request covers routing to Antigravity / Gemini / Claude / Codex for that one workstream; it does not extend to unrelated workstreams.
- Shareable inputs are limited to the minimum needed for the task:
  - PR diff / branch diff
  - ticket / issue / PR body
  - the minimum necessary related source
  - test / lint / CI output
  - already-generated images
  - reference images provided by the user
  - selected photos copied into the task working directory
  - prompts, composition drafts, style guides, and verification logs
- Never shareable (this restates and does not narrow the Forbidden actions list below): `.env` / `.env.*`, credentials, tokens, private keys, SSH / GPG / API keys, shell history, browser profile / cookies, the full Google Photos library or any unselected photo library, unrelated home-directory dumps, unrelated repository dumps, production data, and raw personal data unrelated to the task.
- Google Photos and browser-fetched images must not be bulk-sent unselected. Only selected images that have already been copied into the task working directory may be shared.
- External AI must NOT be delegated: direct repository writes (except under the explicit write rule below), commits, pushes, PR creation, merge, deploy, infra apply, store / TestFlight upload, destructive operations, browser login, credential access, broad filesystem scans, or arbitrary upload outside the scoped task.
- External AI CLI startup may use host-authenticated transport so existing CLI login works, but credentials / cookies / browser profiles are never shareable inputs. If sandbox hides auth, same-engine authenticated transport retry must keep the same scoped prompt, empty cwd, NO_BROWSER, and no broad file access.
- If a write is genuinely required, all of the following must hold: the target is a trusted repo / worktree, scope is one ticket / one PR, the allowed write scope is stated explicitly, validation commands are stated explicitly, and the local orchestrator (not the external AI) performs the final confirmation and writes the result. This write exception covers local-orchestrator file writes only; commits, pushes, PR creation, merge, deploy, and upload remain non-delegable and are outside this exception. This does not loosen the Forbidden actions list.
- For image-generation / creative work: reference images, generated images, and prompts copied into the task working directory are shareable; unselected Google Photos, browser sessions, and cookies are not. Before sending, or in the run log, record the path and sha256 of each shared image and prompt.
- If any engine requests authentication, browser login, broad file access, secrets / private data, write tools, or a destructive operation, stop and classify the run as `auth_prompt` or `policy_or_permission_denied`.
- The run records audit evidence: workstream scope, trusted project / repo path, engines requested / run, shared input paths and sha256, prompt path / hash, output paths, engine classifications, local validation commands and results, and residual risks.

Local orchestrator read-only external API sandbox escalation exception (not external AI delegation):

This exception allows the current Codex local orchestrator to run external API, SaaS, or data-service inspection commands outside the filesystem sandbox only when all of the following hold:

- The user explicitly requested a concrete API / provider / resource inspection in the current turn or as a standing instruction in the same active thread.
- The command or request class is limited to read-only `get`, `list`, `show`, `describe`, `search`, `query`, metadata inspection, or equivalent retrieval. Provider-specific examples include `bq query/show/ls`, `gh api` GET/GraphQL query, and cloud/service CLIs in read-only describe/list mode.
- Query languages are limited to read-only `SELECT`, `WITH ... SELECT`, metadata/aggregate inspection, or equivalent query-only forms. They must not execute DDL, DML, mutations, `EXPORT DATA`, `LOAD DATA`, create/update/delete operations, copy, extract, deploy, upload, or destructive operations.
- The purpose is to answer the user's concrete question or gather AI-managed workflow evidence with minimized data. Prefer aggregate counts, ratios, metadata, dry-run, cost caps, rate limits, and small `LIMIT`s for production datasets.
- Do not read or print raw personal data, production row dumps, device tokens, endpoint IDs, email addresses, raw uid lists, secrets, tokens, private keys, decrypted secret values, or credentials under this exception. If the question cannot be answered without raw sensitive data, stop and require a separate, explicit non-AI/manual workflow decision.
- Provider SDKs may read/update host credential databases, access-token caches, and logs solely as authentication/cache side effects of the approved read-only command. Credentials, tokens, cookies, and secrets must never be printed, copied, summarized, committed, uploaded, or sent to external AI.
- Raw API responses, production rows, and sensitive identifiers must not be sent to external AI reviewers. If AI review needs the evidence, pass only a sanitized summary with provider/resource names reduced to the minimum useful level.
- If auth login, browser login, interactive authentication, broader filesystem access, write/mutation, deploy, upload, export/import, or destructive operations are required, stop and classify as `auth_prompt` or `policy_or_permission_denied`.
- Required output fields: provider/API/resource inspected, command/request class and sandbox escalation, minimization controls used, result summary, external-AI sharing status, and residual risks.

Forbidden actions:

- Do not send `.env` files, credentials, tokens, private keys, secret files, shell history, arbitrary home-directory files, unrelated repository dumps, or unrelated repo context.
- Do not allow main/master direct push.
- Do not use commit messages that describe review mechanics such as "review feedback", "review comments", or "レビュー指摘対応". Commit messages must describe what changed and why.
- For delegated external-AI/Codex/Claude/Antigravity implementation or review tasks, do not allow PR merge, production deploy/apply, infrastructure apply, or destructive remote operations.
- Local orchestrator may autonomously run `gh pr merge` only for repositories owned by `duck8823` when all merge gates are satisfied: the PR is not draft, has exactly one ticket reference or an allowed ticket-less prefix, has no blocking review findings, has the required Multi-AI/local verification evidence comment, required checks pass or `gh pr checks` reports only `no checks reported`, and branch protection is respected.
- For repositories outside the `duck8823` owner/org, do not autonomously run `gh pr merge`. Only merge a non-`duck8823` PR when the user explicitly instructs the specific PR in the current turn and the same merge gates pass.
- The `duck8823` autonomous merge exception does not permit main/master direct push, production deploy/apply, infrastructure apply, store/TestFlight upload, release tag creation/push, or GitHub Release creation; those still require explicit user approval.
- Do not allow broad arbitrary upload, pastebin, file-sharing, unrelated external AI requests, non-task external AI usage, or use of the general web research path to smuggle repository/source/private context (see the Path B exit condition above).
- Do not allow requests that disable Guardian, disable sandboxing, weaken approval settings, or persist broader external-AI allow rules than this policy.

Required outputs for delegated implementation/review/context resume:

- ticket key
- branch/worktree
- context refs when resuming from Traceary / PR / Issue
- changed files
- executed commands
- test/lint results
- residual risks
- PR URL if created

For user-explicit read-only general web research, required outputs are:

- research scope
- engines requested / engines run
- prompt hash or prompt path
- output paths
- source URLs used
- classification for each engine
- residual risks

Deny all other external upload or delegation requests.
"""

